ROBERT TOWNSEND: Sure.

00:07:33.450 --> 00:07:34.470 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:07:34.470 --> 00:07:37.200 align:middle line:84%
Can you give us some
specific details

00:07:37.200 --> 00:07:42.960 align:middle line:84%
about the difference between
the inventories and imports?

00:07:42.960 --> 00:07:49.160 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes, maybe inventories--
we calculate the inventories

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:53.030 align:middle line:90%
when we calculate the NIPA.

00:07:53.030 --> 00:07:57.120 align:middle line:90%
But we subtract the inputs.

00:07:57.120 --> 00:08:04.260 align:middle line:84%
But sometimes we-- maybe
some inventories could be

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:07.560 align:middle line:90%
the inputs in the next period.

00:08:07.560 --> 00:08:12.420 align:middle line:84%
In this period,
we buy something,

00:08:12.420 --> 00:08:14.290 align:middle line:90%
and we do not use them.

00:08:14.290 --> 00:08:15.810 align:middle line:90%
And so they are not imports.

00:08:15.810 --> 00:08:20.220 align:middle line:84%
But in the next period,
they would be the inputs.

00:08:20.220 --> 00:08:25.290 align:middle line:84%
Then, in the next period,
when we recalculate the NIPA,

00:08:25.290 --> 00:08:28.140 align:middle line:90%
we should subtract this part.

00:08:28.140 --> 00:08:32.475 align:middle line:84%
We should subtract
these inventories.

00:08:32.475 --> 00:08:33.350 align:middle line:90%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yes.

00:08:33.350 --> 00:08:37.460 align:middle line:84%
So you've almost
given the answer.

00:08:37.460 --> 00:08:41.659 align:middle line:84%
We want to keep track of the
difference between buying

00:08:41.659 --> 00:08:43.559 align:middle line:90%
and holding versus using.

00:08:43.559 --> 00:08:49.830 align:middle line:84%
So in the productions, the
income statement and so on,

00:08:49.830 --> 00:08:52.520 align:middle line:84%
we have the cost of
producing something.

00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:55.910 align:middle line:84%
So if they take something
out of inventory

00:08:55.910 --> 00:08:59.750 align:middle line:84%
or buy it on the market,
we value it at the cost

00:08:59.750 --> 00:09:04.330 align:middle line:84%
and have it as part of
the cost of production.

00:09:04.330 --> 00:09:06.900 align:middle line:84%
So that's kind of
the flow input.

00:09:06.900 --> 00:09:09.510 align:middle line:84%
Now, if they bought
something on the market

00:09:09.510 --> 00:09:12.900 align:middle line:84%
but didn't utilize it
yet, as in your example,

00:09:12.900 --> 00:09:16.790 align:middle line:84%
then they accumulate
it as inventory.

00:09:16.790 --> 00:09:20.760 align:middle line:84%
And that part is an asset that
appears on the balance sheet.

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:23.400 align:middle line:90%


00:09:23.400 --> 00:09:25.610 align:middle line:84%
So there is a relation
here between the stocks

00:09:25.610 --> 00:09:27.620 align:middle line:90%
and the flows.

00:09:27.620 --> 00:09:31.100 align:middle line:84%
And indeed, in the Thai
data, we have all kinds

00:09:31.100 --> 00:09:34.250 align:middle line:90%
of inventory accounts.

00:09:34.250 --> 00:09:39.170 align:middle line:84%
We have the rice
that they produced

00:09:39.170 --> 00:09:40.950 align:middle line:90%
and didn't actually sell.

00:09:40.950 --> 00:09:43.430 align:middle line:84%
So we have an output
inventory account.

00:09:43.430 --> 00:09:46.320 align:middle line:84%
We have fertilizer
that they buy,

00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:49.200 align:middle line:84%
but they haven't put
on the field yet.

00:09:49.200 --> 00:09:51.320 align:middle line:84%
So that's an input
inventory account.

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:54.410 align:middle line:84%
And those things
are not trivial.

00:09:54.410 --> 00:09:56.570 align:middle line:84%
But the inventory
per se is a way

00:09:56.570 --> 00:09:59.165 align:middle line:90%
of carrying value over time.

00:09:59.165 --> 00:10:01.750 align:middle line:90%


00:10:01.750 --> 00:10:02.670 align:middle line:90%
